Hey John,

 

The southwind heater has a thermostat of some sort. The switch has on/off
and then you twist it, and the more you twist it, the hotter it is supposed
to get. 

 

I am not sure how well it works the temp control works, as shortly after I
installed mine, I ended up finally upgrading my bus to 12V. So I have not
hooked up the heater since. This was a few years ago. I also has a big chuck
of time with the bus off the road for a full repaint/resto job. I thought I
would have the heater in for this winter-but hasn't happened yet.

 

To fix this, I need to pull engine, figure out which parts need to be
swapped for 12V, or some have suggested a different switch.but I think I
need to do more than that. I also need to pull the engine, as I used the
original duct to blower adaptor-that only lasted a short time before it fell
apart. It was NOS, but it was also ~35-40 year old rubber when I went to
install it. It seemed fine when I installed it, but I guess the heat dried
it out, and caused it to fall apart damn fast.  I've got to figure out how
to fabricate an alternate adaptor.

 

